Semilarski v. Prosecutor's Office: Former Deputy Mayor of Tartu will be considered for cassation on August 4
This means that a decision on it is likely to be made in early September.
The courts of the first two instances refused to consider Semilarski's lawsuit, but in April, his cassation appeal was accepted by the State Court.
On 12 December 2019, the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, as its resolution was not within its competence as an administrative court.
The court ruling stated that the complaint contained a claim for compensation for damage caused during criminal proceedings.
"The prosecutor's office and the county court should regulate such issues," Anett Kreutzmann, a spokeswoman for the Tartu courts, previously explained to ERR.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed the ruling in the district court, which on February 5 did not change the decision of the court of first instance.
Now the State Court will have to say its word.
According to Semilarski's defense attorney, attorney-at-law Oliver Nääes, his client had been wrongly suspected of bribery for about two years.
Now he demands that the prosecutor's office refute the untrue allegations against him and compensate him for moral damage.
The reason for filing a complaint to the court were the statements made by the prosecutor for special cases of the Liuna District Prosecutor's Office, Margus Gross, in October 2017, when Semilarski, together with several other at the time deputy mayor of Tartu, Artyom Sverd, was convicted.
"We would like to remind you that when I was detained, the Security Police and the Prosecutor's Office immediately organized a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the leaders of Tartu, one of the most influential local governments, will be in charge.
These public suspicions that hung in the air accompanied me for about two years.
And now that these allegations and suspicions have turned out to be false, the prosecutor's office does not want to say anything about it," Semilarski commented in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Näes, at the press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework in which the prosecutor's office should operate.
"The allegation of bribes and mis-selling turned out to be false, but that's not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia, as well as on Lithuania, that during the investigation phase, representatives of the state should be careful when choosing words so that suspects are not presented before the suspects.
The prosecutor's office is also obliged to do this by the presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, was not observed in this case against Valvo Semilarski," Näes said.
"The public presentation of Semilarski as a serious offender and a bribe-taker in circumstances where the facts underlying the suspicion of bribery are still being clarified is unacceptable for a wrongdoer, which contradicts the presumption of wrongdoer.
As rus.err.ee wrote, Valvo Semilarski, the former deputy mayor of Tartu, will not be prosecuted on bribery charges - the criminal case against him was partially closed in July.
At the same time, the former official is being tried on charges of knowingly violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions on a particularly large scale.
According to the indictment, between 2015 and 2017, the former deputy mayor of Tartu participated more than thirty times in meetings of the city government in making decisions related to companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or managers of the larvae.
According to Gross, in all these cases Semilarski had personal interests, and therefore he had to step aside from participating in decision-making.
Earlier, as rus.err.ee wrote, the prosecutor's office charged Semilarski with suspicion of taking a bribe and violating anti-corruption legislation in conducting transactions on a particularly large scale.
This happened in October 2016, when he was detained along with another deputy mayor, Artem Suvorov (Centrist Party).
Then, the Prosecutor's Office and the Security Police said that there was strong evidence against both deputy mayors.
Both officials then resigned.
Suvorov's case later came to court, which fully acquitted the politician.
The judicial investigation into Valvo Semilarski is still ongoing.
