You put the documents in the briefcase, close the lock  ⁇  at this very moment all the documents are converted into random numbers  ⁇  and send the briefcase to James.
While the briefcase is on its way, you call James to report the code.
After receiving the briefcase, he enters the code, the documents are decrypted, and voila  ⁇  you just sent an encrypted message to James Bond.
(Laughter) A fun example, but it illustrates three important elements of coding.
Code  ⁇  we call it  ⁇ encryption key ⁇ .
It's like a password.
Call James to tell him the lock combination code.
This is called  ⁇ key exchange ⁇   ⁇
guarantee that you will get the encryption key safely from the right place.
And a lock that encodes and decodes the document.
This is called a "coding algorithm."
Using the key, it converts text in documents into random numbers.
A good algorithm will encode in such a way that without a key, the document is very difficult to decrypt.
The importance of encryption is that if someone takes possession of a portfolio and hacks it without the help of an encryption key and an encryption algorithm, he will still not be able to read its contents.
The information will look like a set of random numbers.
Most security systems rely on a secure way to exchange keys to transfer the encryption key to the right location.
However, the rapid development of computing power jeopardizes a number of modern key exchange methods.
Consider one of the most widely used systems today, RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it was estimated that it would take 40 quadrillion years to crack the 426-bit RSA key.
In 1994, just 17 years later, the code was hacked.
As computers became more powerful, we had to use more complex codes.
