One winter morning a few years ago, I was driving to work in Johannesburg, South Africa, and noticed fog hanging over the city.
I drive there almost every day, so I would hardly have paid attention to it before.
Johannesburg is known for its special horizons that I could barely see that morning.
I soon realised it was a huge cloud of polluted air.
The contrast between my usual picturesque environment and that smog-covered sky stirred up something in me.
I was horrified that this city of colorful and picturesque sunsets would be swallowed up by the darkness.
At that moment I had a strong desire to do something, but I didn't know what.
I knew only that I could not stay away.
The main difficulty was that I didn't know much about ecology, air quality management or atmospheric chemistry.
I'm a computer engineer and I was sure I couldn't handle this problem with the help of code.
(Laughter) Who am I to make a difference?
But I was a resident of this city.
In the years that followed, I learned one very important lesson  ⁇  a lesson that must be taken seriously if we are to have a better future.
Even if you are not an expert in any field, your outside experience can be the key to solving complex problems in this field.
Sometimes your unique vision can turn into an extraordinary idea that will take everything off the ground, but you must be bold enough to try it.
This is the only way out.
Even then I realized that in order to at least try to change the situation for the better, first I would have to understand air pollution, so I became a student again.
At the very beginning of my research, I learned that air pollution is the most important danger to the environment.
According to the World Health Organization, nearly 14 percent of deaths worldwide in 2012 were caused by air pollution in homes and ambient air pollution, which is especially common in low- and middle-income countries.
Air pollution alone causes more deaths each year than malaria or HIV/AIDS.
In Africa, the number of premature deaths due to poor sanitation or malnutrition among children is in no comparison with the number of deaths due to air pollution, and this comes at a huge economic cost with more than 400 mA of development:
Now in my work I am exploring new opportunities in the field of artificial intelligence, where a symbiotic relationship between man and machine will help find a favorable basis for making the right decisions.
As we studied air pollution, it became clear that we needed to find a way to make better decisions to control air pollution, and given the magnitude of the problem, we needed to do it together.
So I decided to meet people who work in this field.
I started meeting with officials from Johannesburg and other nearby cities, I also engaged the local scientific community and made some cold calls.
The contact-building process I undertook helped me gain a deeper understanding of the problem.
It also helped me not fall into the trap that my colleagues often fall into when trying to innovate when we quickly apply technology before we are clearly aware of the problem.
I started thinking about what I could do to improve the situation.
I just started asking myself how I could effectively combine all my programming and artificial intelligence skills with the experiences of people I met.
I wanted to create an online air quality management platform that would identify patterns in pollution, look into the future and determine what we should expect.
I was determined to put my idea into practice, but faced with uncertainty, I had no guarantees of success.
I only had a certain set of engineering skills that I had acquired in my profession (Laughter) and that people dealing with air pollution had not had for years.
I realized that sometimes just one fresh look, some new skills create the conditions for the appearance of something outstanding.
Willpower and imagination are our guiding light, empowering us to find new ways and bypass challenges.
Armed with an in-depth understanding of air pollution and having studied the decades-old information on the concentration of pollutants and meteorological conditions in Johannesburg and beyond, I am excited to be setting up with my colleagues from South Africa.
The software system analyzes historical and real-time data to identify spatial and temporal trends.
Then we used new machine learning technology to predict the level of pollution for different pollutants a few days in advance.
This means that residents can make better decisions about their movements and where to live for their families.
We will be able to predict pollution cases in advance, calculate the culprits of pollution, who will be forced by the authorities to reduce the scope of their activities.
With scenario planning, urban planners will be able to make the right decisions in infrastructure development, such as residential settlements and industrial areas.
We completed testing of our technology, which lasted about 120 days, covering all of South Africa.
The results were welcomed when we demonstrated the close relationship between the forecast data and the data we received locally.
Thanks to our leadership, we have created advanced, innovative technologies that will be able to predict air quality with unprecedented accuracy, improving the city on which not so long ago I was driving in one winter morning, ⁇  he said.
And here's my conclusion: what if I didn't study air pollution then?
What if I didn't express concern about the state of the environment and just hoped that someone somewhere was already dealing with this problem?
That's what I've learned: when we tackle a complex enterprise that contributes to what we strongly believe in, it's important to focus on success and consider the consequences of inaction.
We must not go astray in the face of obstacles and difficulties, this should motivate us even more.
Wherever you are, when you realize that your natural curiosity is excited by something and that's what excites you, and you have crazy and bold ideas, and maybe it's beyond your competence, ask:
Why not act and solve the problem, as you can, in your own way?
And perhaps you will be pleasantly surprised.
Thank you.
