Today I would like to show you how in the future we will do different things.
I believe that soon our buildings and machines will be self-assembling, will reproduce and repair themselves.
So I'm going to show you what I consider to be the current stage of industrial development, and then compare that with some natural systems.
So, at the current stage of industrial development, we have skyscrapers - 2.5 years, from 500,000 to a million parts, quite complex, new stunning technologies in steel, concrete and glass.
We have amazing machines that can take us into space - 5 years, 2.5 million parts.
But on the other hand, if you look at natural systems, we see proteins of two million species that can gather in 10,000 nanoseconds, or a DNA chain with three billion basic pairs that we can copy in one hour.
So, for all their complexity, natural systems are extremely efficient, far more efficient than anything we can build, far more complex than anything we can build.
They are much more energy efficient.
They almost never make a mistake.
And they can rebuild themselves over a long life.
So, there is something very interesting in natural systems.
And if we can move this into our man-made environment, our way of creating things will have tremendous potential.
And I think the key is self-assembly.
So, if we want to use self-assembly in our physical environment, I think four key factors need to be considered.
First: we need to decipher the complexity of what we want to build - our buildings and machines.
And we need to decompose them into a simple sequence - the basic DNA of construction processes.
Then we'll need programmable parts that can understand this sequence and use it to swerve or reassemble.
We will need a certain amount of energy, which will enable all this, make the parts able to assemble according to the program.
And we need some sort of back-up bug-fixing system to ensure we build what we want.
I'm going to show you some of the projects that we're working on with our EmAITi colleagues to achieve this self-assembling future.
The first two are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These are projects - large-scale reconfigurable robots - 2.5 and 3.5 meter proteins.
Mechanical electrical devices and sensors are built into them.
You paint what you want to roll into a sequence of angles - minus 120, minus 120, 0, 120, minus 120 - something like that; a sequence of angles or turns, and you send that sequence along the cord.
Each block receives its own message - minus 120. It turns this corner, checks if everything is correct and transmits information to a neighbor.
And these are brilliant scientists, engineers, designers who worked on this project.
And I think it actually reveals the question: Is there a different scale possible here?
I mean, thousands of dollars, lots of man hours to make this 2.5 meter robot.
Will we actually be able to scale up? Will we actually be able to integrate robotics into every part?
The next project solves this issue, considers a passive nature or tries to obtain a modified programability passively.
But he goes a step further and tries to get a real calculation.
At its core it has the most fundamental building block of computing, the logical element of a digital integrated circuit directly in each part.
It's an "I-NOT" element.
You have one tetrahedron, an element that will do all the calculations, and two tetrahedra for input.
One for inputting information by the user is the way you put bricks.
Another for information from the previous laid brick.
And then it displays information in three-dimensional space.
So this means that the user can start to move bricks in the right direction.
His calculations are based on what was done earlier and what you told him to do.
And now it starts moving in three-dimensional space - up or down.
On the left hand side, [1,1] input equals 0 at output, moving down.
On the right side, [0.0] input is 1 on output, which means upward movement.
And what really matters is that our structures now contain blueprints of what we want to build.
They contain all the information about what was built.
So that means we have some form of self-reproduction.
In this case, I call it self-managed reproduction because the structures contain clear blueprints.
If there are errors, you can replace the part.
All local information is saved so you know how to fix it.
So you may have something that moves and reads information and can pass it from one part to another.
It is built directly inside, without external control.
The latest project I'll show you is called Shifted Circuits, and this is perhaps the most exciting example of what we have now from passive self-assembling systems.
It combines the ability to reconfigure and program and creates a completely passive system.
At the core we have a chain of elements.
All elements are completely identical, and displaced.
So every chain or element wants to turn right or left.
And when you assemble the chain, you'll essentially program it.
You tell each block where it should turn: right or left.
So when you shake the chain, it folds into the configuration you programmed - in this case into a spiral, or in this case, two cubes next to each other.
So in general you can program any three-dimensional shape - or one-dimensional, two-dimensional - from these completely passive circuits.
So what does this tell us about the future?
I think it tells us that there are new opportunities for self-assembly, replication, repair in our physical structures, buildings, machines.
New software is possible in these parts.
And from here, you have new possibilities in computing.
We will have spatial computers.
Imagine that our buildings, bridges, cars, all our bricks could do calculations.
It's an amazing parallel and distributed computing power, new design features.
This is an incredible potential.
