It is believed that behind the wheel of a car can only be sighted people.
Until recently, it was believed that for the blind, safe and independent driving is an impossible task.
Hello, I am Dennis Hong, and we give the blind freedom and independence by developing a car for the visually impaired.
Before talking about this car for the blind, I will briefly talk about another project I worked on, called the DARPA Urban Challenge.
The project was to create a self-driving robot car.
The driver presses "start" and without his participation the car reaches its destination.
In 2007, our team won half a million dollars, finishing third in this competition.
Around the same time, the National Federation of the Blind, or NSF, tasked the research committee with developing a vehicle that can be independently and safely operated by the blind.
We decided to try our hand because we thought,  ⁇ Hey, what's that difficult?
We already have an autonomous car.
Let's put a blind man in it - and it's all over, right?"
(Laughter) But we are deeply mistaken.
The NFS wanted not just a car that would transport the blind, but a car that the blind person could independently drive.
So we had to take it all off and start from scratch.
So, to test this crazy idea, we developed a small car buggy prototype to test the feasibility of the project.
And in the summer of 2009, we invited blind youth from all corners of the country and gave them the opportunity to test this car.
It was an amazing experience.
But the catch is that this car was designed to operate in a strictly controlled environment, namely in a level closed parking lot, where even lanes are limited by red signal cones.
Due to this success, we decided to take the next big step and develop a real car that could be driven on real roads.
So how does it work?
Well, it's quite a complex system, but let me explain, perhaps even simplify it.
So, it includes three components.
It is tactile perception, calculation and non-visual interfaces.
Since the driver can't see anything, the system needs to understand the environment and gather information for the driver.
An initial parameter meter is used for this.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration, like a person's inner ear.
This information is then transmitted to a GPS device to assess the location of the vehicle.
Two cameras are used to detect lane on the road
and three laser rangefinders.
Lasers scan the space around the car to detect various objects: an approaching oncoming or overtaking car, any obstacles encountered on the road or around the car.
Then all this huge amount of information is fed into the computer and the computer performs two steps.
First of all, it is processing this information to get an idea of the space: identifying lanes on the road, identifying obstacles, and then communicating this information to the driver.
The system is also smart enough to calculate the safest way to drive a car.
So, we can also give advice on how to operate the machine.
But the problem is, how do you convey this information and instructions to an blind person who does not have the quick and accurate response needed to drive?
For this purpose, we have developed a number of interface technologies for the blind:
A 3D ping sound system, a vibrating vest, a steering wheel with sound signals, a special foot prosthesis, and even shoes that put pressure on the leg.
But today we will only talk about three types of these special interfaces.
The first interface is called DriveGrip.
This is a pair of gloves with motors on the joints of the fingers, instructing the driver how to drive: direction and corner.
Another device is SpeedStrip.
Initially it is a massage chair.
Vibration is used to transmit speed information to the driver, as well as to guide the use of gas and brake pedals.
So, here you can see how the computer perceives the space around the car. And since the vibration cannot be seen, red LEDs are installed on the driver to demonstrate the process.
This is sensory data, which is transmitted to devices through a computer.
DriveGrip and SpeedStrip devices are very efficient.
But the problem is that these are training prompts.
They don't actually give freedom of control, do they?
The onboard computer gives the driver commands: "left", "right", "add speed", "stop".
We call him "an annoying passenger from the back seat."
So we are moving away from learning prompts and focusing on information devices.
An excellent example of such an interface is AirPix.
This is a kind of monitor for the blind.
A small panel with many holes through which compressed air enters, thereby creating images.
A blind person can bring his palm to this panel and "see" the lanes on the roadway and obstacles.
The driver can also change the frequency with which the air comes out and possibly the temperature of the air.
That is, it is an interface for displaying multidimensional data.
So, here you see the left and right camera of the car, and how the computer processes and sends this information to the AirPix panel.
Here we demonstrate a simulator, a blind man driving a car using AirPix.
This simulator proved to be very useful for training blind drivers, as well as for quickly checking ideas on the use of different types of special interfaces.
That's how this system works in short.
After all, this is a prototype car for the blind. And it will not be released on the roadway until they are convinced of its absolute safety.
And I truly believe this is likely.
Still, will society accept such a radical idea?
How much will auto insurance rules change?
On what conditions will the driver's license be issued?
Beyond the technological challenges, there are so many pitfalls that must be overcome before this becomes a reality.
Of course, the main goal of this project is to develop a car for the blind.
However, it is possible that the spin-off technologies developed during this project will be an invaluable contribution to our lives.
Our sensors work regardless of the time of day, fog and rain.
We can use these technologies together with new special interfaces to improve the safety of cars for the blind.
Or for the blind. Find them use in everyday appliances, in educational institutions, in offices.
Just imagine: a teacher in the classroom writes on a blackboard, and a blind student can see and read what is written using these special interfaces.
This is priceless.
So what I showed you today is just the beginning.
Thank you very much.
